I"…<p>On Cyber Monday, I took advantage of <a href="https://www.yubico.com">Yubico</a>â€™s 2-for-1 YubiKey deal and got two <a href="https://www.yubico.com/products/yubikey-hardware/yubikey4/">YubiKey 4</a>s for the price on one ($40).</p>

<p>My understanding is that usually these keys are used as a 2nd factor in 2-factor authentication schemes. In this capacity it works with Google and Dropbox, as well as a number of password managers including LastPass, dashlane, Keepass, and a <a href="https://www.yubico.com/applications/password-management/">number of others</a>. Also, thereâ€™s <a href="https://www.yubico.com/products/yubikey-hardware/">a breakdown of some of the technical differences between models of YubiKeys</a>.</p>

<p>However I was more interested in using it to store a PGP key, so that I might be able to use one PGP key on any computer I might find myself. I also wanted this PGP Key to be an RSA key of length of 4,096, so I needed either a YubiKey 4 or a YubiKey 4 Nano. As I say above, I went for the YubiKey 4.</p>

<!-- more -->

<p>(Note that according to <a href="https://www.yubico.com/products/yubikey-hardware/yubikey4/#toggle-id-2">the YubiKey 4â€™s FAQ section</a>, â€œOn the same YubiKey, at the same time, you can use U2F to secure your Gmail account, access services like LastPass, as well as secure your communication using applets loaded on your device, such as the OpenPGP applet.â€)</p>

<p>The most immediate reason I wanted to be able to take my private keys with me when I left a room was that I didnâ€™t want them on my work computer.</p>

<p><strong>Note</strong>: Iâ€™m not an expert. While I think Iâ€™ve gotten pretty far with this, I donâ€™t understand everything yet. This blog post is mostly for my personal reference of how I got this to work, while consulting a combination of tutorials written by others linked to just below. If that doesnâ€™t sound like what youâ€™re looking for, check out the tutorials themselves and close this tabâ€“ no hard feelings!</p>

<p><strong>Note 2 (October 2017)</strong>: Iâ€™ve added a note below about <strong>a security issue</strong> related to this procedure called the â€œInfineon RSA Key Generation Issueâ€. This issue was announced publicly in October of 2017. See below for more, but <a href="https://www.yubico.com/keycheck/">hereâ€™s Yubicoâ€™s page on the issue</a> and <a href="https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/crypto-failure-cripples-millions-of-high-security-keys-750k-estonian-ids/">an Ars Technica article about it</a>.</p>

<p>I have a basic understanding of PGP (I also have <a href="https://sts10.github.io/2015/07/01/my-basic-understanding-of-pgp-encryption.html">an earlier post outlining some basics of PGP</a> if you like), but I knew setting up and using a YubiKey would be tricky for me and I still donâ€™t have a full grasp of it. So I spent the $40 and figured I could figure it out. Hereâ€™s what I did.</p>

<p><img src="https://hao0uteruy2io8071pzyqz13-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/YubiKey-4-1000-2016-444x444.png" alt="A YubiKey 4" /></p>

<h2 id="what-i-did-tutorials-i-found">What I Did (Tutorials I Found)</h2>

<p>To do this I consulted these two tutorials: <a href="https://trmm.net/Yubikey">this one from Trammel Hudson</a> and <a href="https://www.yubico.com/support/knowledge-base/categories/articles/use-yubikey-openpgp/">a more official one on the Yubico website</a>.</p>

<p>Thereâ€™s also <a href="https://github.com/drduh/YubiKey-Guide">this drduh gist</a>, however itâ€™s does everything though the command line and is done on a Linux Debian installation (not MacOS).</p>

<p>Thereâ€™s also <a href="https://www.gnupg.org/gph/en/manual.html">this GnuPG.org manual</a> (which has a <a href="https://www.gnupg.org/gph/en/manual.html#MANAGEMENT">key management section</a>) that Iâ€™ll reference later.</p>

<h2 id="pgp-strategy--goals">PGP Strategy / Goals</h2>

<p>As mentioned above, my goal was to have one PGP key that would follow me around from computer to computer. And rather than use a regular USB key to shuttle my private keys to each computer, I figured there was a more secure option with similar portability, which seems to be what the YubiKey 4 is made for (itâ€™s small enough to live on key chain).</p>

<p>So Iâ€™d make this key and put it on the YubiKey. This key pairâ€™s public key would (hopefully) never be uploaded to a public key server. The reason I didnâ€™t want it on any public key servers is that Iâ€™d be able to <strong>completely delete it</strong> and make a new one without having to revoke it from public key servers. When I left BuzzFeed I had to revoke the key I made and associated with my buzzfeed.com email address. Now when you search â€œSam Schlinkertâ€ on the MIT server, you see two keys:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>pub  4096R/B80500F2 2015-09-16 Sam Schlinkert &lt;sschlinkert@gmail.com&gt;
Fingerprint=EF45 36E5 6440 EF4D 5D31  E82A 5BF6 E5C2 B805 00F2 
---------------
pub  4096R/3CC91D33 2015-06-24 *** KEY REVOKED *** [not verified] Sam Schlinkert &lt;sam.schlinkert@buzzfeed.com&gt;
Fingerprint=56AB EFDF 1373 7728 2394  B9FF 77D9 AF85 3CC9 1D33 
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>As you can see, while the revoked key is relatively well labeled as â€œREVOKEDâ€, itâ€™s still there, meaning that thereâ€™d be another revoked key every time I deleted and made a new key pair for the YubiKey. If I reovked my keys frequently, this search result page would keep getting more cluttered.</p>

<p>That said, I still wanted to maintain a key on the public serversâ€“ ostensibly for initial contact. Since I already have a key on the servers, I figured Iâ€™d just keep that for now.  (<a href="https://pgp.mit.edu/pks/lookup?op=get&amp;search=0x5BF6E5C2B80500F2">here it is</a> on MITâ€™s server). I still have it linked to from my Twitter account.</p>

<p>My inspiration for prioritizing this ability to recycle my (relatively) more-secure key (the one on the YubiKey in this situation) frequently and easily is this <a href="https://blog.filippo.io/giving-up-on-long-term-pgp/">blog post by Filippo Valsorda</a> and <a href="https://gist.github.com/grugq/03167bed45e774551155">this Gist on â€œOperational PGPâ€</a> by <a href="https://twitter.com/thegrugq">@thegrugq</a>.</p>

<p>In <a href="https://blog.filippo.io/giving-up-on-long-term-pgp/">his blog post</a> about why heâ€™s giving up on long-term PGP, Valsorda writes:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>But the real issues I realized are more subtle. I never felt confident in the security of my long term keys. The more time passed, the more I would feel uneasy about any specific key. Yubikeys would get exposed to hotel rooms. Offline keys would sit in a far away drawer or safe. Vulnerabilities would be announced. USB devices would get plugged in.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>A long term key is as secure as the minimum common denominator of your security practices over its lifetime. Itâ€™s the weak link.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>Worse, long term keys patterns like collecting signatures and printing fingerprints on business cards discourage practices that would otherwise be obvious hygiene: rotating keys often, having different keys for different devices, compartmentalization. It actually encourages expanding the attack surface by making backups of the key.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>I learned more from <a href="https://gist.github.com/grugq/03167bed45e774551155">thegrugqâ€™s Gist on â€œOperational PGPâ€</a>:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>A more secure mitigation against key loss is to generate new keys frequently, use them for specific operations, and then destroy them. For example, when traveling, create a new Travel PGP Key and use that until you are back home. That way if anyone compromises your travel laptop they only breach the compartment for the duration of your travel. The impact of the compromise is contained by the limitation on the utility of the PGP key.</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>So â€“ more keys, more often.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Given that the key on my YubiKey wonâ€™t be public, I would be able to recycle them often or between â€œoperationsâ€. So maybe every few months, or if I start using PGP more, every few weeks.</p>

<p>One downside to this strategy is that the key on the YubiKey wonâ€™t be very useful for authenticating myself. However I have that public-facing key linked to on my verified Twitter account as well as on my Facebook account, which I think replaces my need to have any of my PGP keys signed by members of a web of trust.</p>

<h2 id="preparation">Preparation</h2>

<p><strong>OK letâ€™s get a new, fresh key pair on to my new YubiKey 4.</strong></p>

<p>From the <a href="https://www.yubico.com/support/knowledge-base/categories/articles/use-yubikey-openpgp/">official tutorial</a> I learned that, since I have a YubiKey 4, I did NOT need to change the mode to enable CCID: â€œNote that all YubiKey 4 devices and all YubiKey NEO devices are now shipped with CCID mode enabled by default.â€</p>

<p>I also made sure I had the latest version of <a href="https://gpgtools.org/gpgsuite.html">GPG Suite</a> installed.</p>

<p>(For the record Iâ€™m running OS X Yosemite (10.10.5).)</p>

<p>I also already had an up-to-date version of GnuPG installed on my command line. When I run: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gpg --version</code> I get the following:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>gpg (GnuPG/MacGPG2) 2.0.30
libgcrypt 1.6.6
Copyright (C) 2015 Free Software Foundation, Inc.
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>If <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gpg</code> gives you version 1, you may have GPG version 2 but need to use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gpg2</code> on the command line. If running <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gpg2 --version</code> gives you a version over 2, youâ€™ll need to use the <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gpg2</code> command everywhere you see me use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gpg</code> below.</p>

<p>In order to use an RSA key with a length of 4,096 with your YubiKey 4, youâ€™ll need to use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gpg</code> version 2 (as the tutorial notes: â€œIf you are using a YubiKey 4 and want to work with 4096 key sizes, you need to use GPG v 2â€)</p>

<h2 id="a-choice-orphan-vs-mothership">A Choice: â€œOrphanâ€ vs. â€œMothershipâ€</h2>

<p><strong>IMPORTANT SECURITY UPDATE (October 2017): A security issue has been discovered that affects, among other things, OpenPGP functionality of the YubiKey 4 platform.</strong> Itâ€™s been labeled the â€œInfineon RSA Key Generation Issueâ€ by Yubico, and it comes into play in the section of this guide below. <em>Handling and mitigating this issue is a bit over my head, but I thought I should add a note here. Please rely heavily on the links provided below and/or your own research of this issue.</em></p>

<p><a href="https://www.yubico.com/keycheck/">From the Yubico notice on their website</a>: Yubikey 4 / 4C / 4 nano Versions 4.2.6-4.3.4 are â€œpossibly affected - Use of onboard RSA key generation with PIV smart card and OpenPGP card onboard RSA key generation.â€ <a href="https://www.yubico.com/keycheck/firmware_guide">Hereâ€™s how to find out what version your YubiKey is</a>. Note that Yubico <a href="https://www.yubico.com/keycheck/">says that</a> â€œYubico has addressed this issue in all shipments of YubiKey 4, YubiKey 4 Nano, and YubiKey 4C, since June 6, 2017,â€ so if you bought your YubiKey after that date, you should be OK.</p>

<p>Hereâ€™s <a href="https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/crypto-failure-cripples-millions-of-high-security-keys-750k-estonian-ids/">Ars Technicaâ€™s write-up of the issue</a>.</p>

<p>From <a href="https://www.yubico.com/keycheck/mitigation_recommendations">the relevant Yubico mitigation page</a>:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The mitigation strategy for OpenPGP is to generate keys outside of the YubiKey and import them onto the device. For more information refer to the Yubico Knowledge Base document â€œ<a href="https://www.yubico.com/support/knowledge-base/categories/articles/use-yubikey-openpgp/#generatelocal">Generating the key on your local system</a>â€.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Given this mitigation advice, my understanding is that if your YubiKey is one of the affected versions, you are advised NOT to generate your PGP key on your YubiKey (a process I describe as the â€œorphanâ€ method below). Instead, you should generate your GPGP keys on your computer, and then put them onto your YubiKey (a process I describe as the â€œmothershipâ€ method below).</p>

<p>If you have GPG keys that you generated on your affected YubiKey, youâ€™re to revoke them and then trash them and generate a new pair on a device that is not your affect YubiKey (like your laptop). This process is the very one I attempt to describe below, however please convince yourself that these actions will result in key that is safe enough for you to use before proceeding. Again, I am far from an expertâ€“ Iâ€™m just outlining a procedure that worked for me.</p>

<p>If you have an existing key or keys that you think may be affected, <a href="https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2017/10/crypto-failure-cripples-millions-of-high-security-keys-750k-estonian-ids/">the Ars Techncia article</a> links to <a href="https://keychest.net/roca">this site</a>, which claims to allow you to test your keys by submitting your <em>public</em> key.</p>

<p><strong>END UPDATE</strong></p>

<p>As the <a href="https://www.yubico.com/support/knowledge-base/categories/articles/use-yubikey-openpgp/">official tutorial</a> explains:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Before you begin, decide if you want to generate the private key on the YubiKey device, or if you want to generate the private key off of the YubiKey and then move the subkeys to the YubiKey. For greater security, we recommend that you store your subkeys on the device (therefore, generate your private key off of the device).</p>
</blockquote>

<p>So our choices are â€œGenerating Your OpenPGP Key Directly on your YubiKeyâ€ or â€œGenerating the key on your local systemâ€. Iâ€™m a little confused by the differences between these two methods. The idea of generating the key on the YubiKey makes sense to meâ€“ the YubiKey is independent of the computer weâ€™re using, like an â€œorphanâ€. Since the other method uses the computer to generate the keys, then has us move them to the card, I think of it as the â€œmothershipâ€ procedure.</p>

<p>Given my reading of the rather cryptic sentence in the tutorialâ€™s introduction: â€œFor greater security, we recommend that you store your subkeys on the device (therefore, generate your private key off of the device)â€, I figured the â€œmothershipâ€ procedure was a more secure choice.</p>

<p>Thus I decided to generate my private key not on my YubiKey but rather on my computer, and then move them to my YubiKey (i.e. the â€œmothershipâ€ procedure).</p>

<h2 id="generating-a-new-key-pair-on-my-computer">Generating a New Key Pair on my Computer</h2>

<p>At this point, I switched to <a href="https://trmm.net/Yubikey">the Hudson tutorial</a>, skipping down to the section called â€œCreate your keyâ€. (The reason I followed Hudsonâ€™s tutorial at this point is actually because I hadnâ€™t found the official tutorial yet, but Iâ€™m going to keep writing this as if I meant to do all this in the order that I did it.)</p>

<p>Using the GPG Keychain application included in <a href="https://gpgtools.org/gpgsuite.html">GPG Suite</a>, I generated a new key pair as the Hudson tutorial describes. The only difference is that I specified a length of 4,096, since I knew the YubiKey 4 could handle that length. My new keyâ€™s Key ID was <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">03FC30EE</code>, which will be important to have handy for the rest of this.</p>

<p>I also followed Hudsonâ€™s instruction to create a second subkey for signing, as he says thatâ€™s necessary when using cards (like YubiKey)â€“ however I again made mine 4096 long:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>By default GPG Keychain tool create the primary key that has all access and one encryption subkey. For the cards you need to create a second subkey for signing. Double click on your key to bring up the Key Inspector window, select Subkeys and click + to create a new one of type RSA (sign only) and of length 2048.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Since I was just learning I also did NOT export my key (in other words I did NOT â€œAt this point you should export your key and save it somewhere safely offline.â€), nor did I upload my new public key to a key server, for reasons stated above. However I did generate a revoke certificate, just in case I later uploaded the public key, either on purpose or accidentally. I saved the revoke certificate to my computerâ€™s hard drive and an external hard drive.</p>

